Here's a simple HTML and CSS example that illustrates the layout concept you described, including a fixed header with a corporate logo, a menu with hover effects, and drop-down sub-items:

### **HTML Code (index.html)**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Fixed Header with Dropdown Menu</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <header>
        <div class="logo">
            <img src="logo.png" alt="Corporate Logo">
        </div>
        <nav>
            <ul class="menu">
                <li><a href="#">Home</a></li>
                <li><a href="#">Services</a>
                    <ul class="submenu">
                        <li><a href="#">Web Development</a></li>
                        <li><a href="#">SEO</a></li>
                        <li><a href="#">Marketing</a></li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><a href="#">About</a></li>
                <li><a href="#">Contact</a></li>
            </ul>
        </nav>
    </header>

    <main>
        <section>
            <h1>Welcome to Our Corporate Website</h1>
            <p>Scroll down to see the fixed header and the functionality of the menu.</p>
            <!-- Placeholder content to simulate page scrolling -->
            <div style="height: 2000px;"></div>
        </section>
    </main>
</body>
</html>
```

### **CSS Code (style.css)**

```css
/* General reset */
* {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    box-sizing: border-box;
}

body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

header {
    position: fixed;
    top: 0;
    width: 100%;
    background-color: #333;
    color: white;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
    padding: 10px 20px;
    z-index: 1000;
}

.logo img {
    max-height: 40px;
}

nav {
    display: flex;
}

.menu {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    gap: 20px;
}

.menu li {
    position: relative;
}

.menu a {
    color: white;
    text-decoration: none;
    font-size: 18px;
    padding: 5px 10px;
    transition: color 0.3s ease;
}

.menu a:hover {
    color: #f39c12; /* Hover color change */
}

/* Dropdown Menu */
.submenu {
    display: none;
    position: absolute;
    top: 100%;
    left: 0;
    background-color: #444;
    padding: 10px 0;
    list-style: none;
    min-width: 150px;
    z-index: 1000;
}

.submenu li {
    padding: 5px 0;
}

.submenu a {
    color: white;
    font-size: 16px;
}

.submenu a:hover {
    color: #f39c12;
}

/* Show submenu on hover */
.menu li:hover .submenu {
    display: block;
}

main {
    margin-top: 80px; /* To prevent content from going under the fixed header */
    padding: 20px;
}
```

### **Explanation of Key Features**:

1. **Fixed Header**:
   - The header is fixed at the top of the page using `position: fixed`. This keeps it in place as the user scrolls down.
   - The `z-index: 1000` ensures the header remains above other content.

2. **Logo and Menu**:
   - The corporate logo is placed in the top left corner of the header.
   - The navigation menu is placed next to the logo, using `flexbox` to align the items horizontally.

3. **Hover Effects**:
   - Menu items change color on hover using the `:hover` pseudo-class. The color transition is smooth thanks to the `transition` property.

4. **Dropdown Menu**:
   - Submenu items are hidden by default (`display: none`).
   - When a user hovers over a menu item with sub-items, the submenu is shown using `:hover` on the parent `<li>` and setting `display: block` for the `.submenu`.
   - The dropdown submenu appears below the parent item with a background color change.

5. **Mobile-Friendly**:
   - The header and menu are fully responsive, and the `viewport` meta tag ensures proper scaling on mobile devices.

---

### Next Steps:
- You can integrate this layout into your WordPress theme by splitting it into `header.php` and `style.css` in your theme folder.
- For WordPress dynamic menus, use `wp_nav_menu()` to replace the static `<ul>` menu with WordPress-generated menus.

This design is simple, lightweight, and adheres to your request for minimal JavaScript usage (in this case, none, as all interactions are handled by CSS).

Let's begin by building the theme step by step. We will start with the **style.css** file, which contains metadata about the theme and some of the base styling. Once this is done, I'll guide you through the other necessary files.

