### Instructions:
1. Create a folder for your theme, for example, `my-custom-theme`, inside the `/wp-content/themes/` directory of your WordPress installation.
2. Save this `style.css` file in the root of the `my-custom-theme` folder.

Once this is done, let me know, and we'll move on to the next file: **header.php**.

Now, let's move on to the **functions.php** file. This file is where you will register the navigation menu and enqueue the styles for the theme.

### 3. **functions.php**

```php
<?php
// Register theme support for title tag and post thumbnails
function my_custom_theme_setup() {
    // Enable support for dynamic title tag
    add_theme_support('title-tag');

    // Enable support for post thumbnails
    add_theme_support('post-thumbnails');

    // Register a primary menu location
    register_nav_menus(array(
        'primary' => __('Primary Menu', 'my-custom-theme'),
    ));
}
add_action('after_setup_theme', 'my_custom_theme_setup');

// Enqueue styles and scripts
function my_custom_theme_assets() {
    // Enqueue main stylesheet
    wp_enqueue_style('my-custom-theme-style', get_stylesheet_uri());

    // Optionally, enqueue a Google font or other fonts here
    // wp_enqueue_style('my-custom-google-font', 'https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto:wght@400;700&display=swap');

    // Enqueue scripts for dropdown functionality if needed (though not necessary since CSS handles it)
    // wp_enqueue_script('my-custom-theme-scripts', get_template_directory_uri() . '/assets/js/main.js', array('jquery'), null, true);
}
add_action('wp_enqueue_scripts', 'my_custom_theme_assets');
```

### Instructions:
1. Save this file as `functions.php` in your theme folder (`my-custom-theme`).
2. Create an empty directory in your theme folder for the image: `assets/images/`, and add your logo image named `logo.png` inside.

#### Explanation:
- This file registers the **Primary Menu** location and enqueues the theme’s stylesheet.
- You can add additional scripts or fonts (like Google Fonts) if necessary by uncommenting the appropriate lines.
- The `after_setup_theme` hook is used to add theme support for title tags and post thumbnails, ensuring compatibility with WordPress standards.

Once you’ve saved this file, you should now be able to go to the WordPress Admin Dashboard, set up a menu under **Appearance > Menus**, and assign it to the **Primary Menu** location.

After you’ve completed this, let me know, and we’ll move on to the next file: **footer.php**.

To change the color of the text in the menu items when a user hovers over them, you can achieve this using simple CSS. Here's how you can modify your existing CSS to ensure the color change happens when the user hovers over the menu items:

### Updated CSS for Hover Effect on Menu Items:

```css
/* General reset */
* {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    box-sizing: border-box;
}

body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

header {
    position: fixed;
    top: 0;
    width: 100%;
    background-color: #333;
    color: white;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
    padding: 10px 20px;
    z-index: 1000;
}

.logo img {
    max-height: 40px;
}

nav {
    display: flex;
}

.menu {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    gap: 20px;
}

.menu li {
    position: relative;
}

.menu a {
    color: white;
    text-decoration: none;
    font-size: 18px;
    padding: 5px 10px;
    transition: color 0.3s ease;
}

/* Hover effect to change color when hovering over menu items */
.menu a:hover {
    color: #f39c12; /* Change this color to whatever you want the hover color to be */
}

/* Dropdown Menu */
.submenu {
    display: none;
    position: absolute;
    top: 100%;
    left: 0;
    background-color: #444;
    padding: 10px 0;
    list-style: none;
    min-width: 150px;
    z-index: 1000;
}

.submenu li {
    padding: 5px 0;
}

.submenu a {
    color: white;
    font-size: 16px;
}

/* Hover effect for submenu items */
.submenu a:hover {
    color: #f39c12; /* Change this color to match your hover effect for submenu */
}

/* Show submenu on hover */
.menu li:hover .submenu {
    display: block;
}

main {
    margin-top: 80px; /* To prevent content from going under the fixed header */
    padding: 20px;
}
```

### Explanation:
1. **Hover Effect for Menu Items**: The CSS rule `.menu a:hover` changes the text color when a user hovers over any menu item. In this case, the color is set to `#f39c12` (a yellowish color). You can replace this with any color you'd like.

2. **Hover Effect for Submenu Items**: Similarly, for the submenu items, `.submenu a:hover` applies the hover color change when a user hovers over a submenu link.

3. **Smooth Transition**: The `transition: color 0.3s ease;` property is added to the menu links, so the color change occurs smoothly over 0.3 seconds.

### Example of Color Customization:
If you want to use a different color for the hover effect, simply replace `#f39c12` with any valid color code, such as:
- **Red**: `#ff0000`
- **Blue**: `#0000ff`
- **Green**: `#00ff00`

